High bias → oversimplified model
High variance → overfitted model

Good models balance both.

Statistical Learning Theory

Developed largely by Vladimir Vapnik and others.

Key idea:

Learning is about minimizing:

Expected Risk

but we only observe finite samples.

The challenge is estimating future performance from limited data.

PAC Learning

Probably Approximately Correct (PAC) learning asks:

How many examples are needed to learn a good model with high probability?

A concept is PAC-learnable if it can be learned efficiently from a finite number of examples.

This provides theoretical guarantees on learning.

VC Dimension

The VC Dimension measures model capacity.

Low VC dimension → simple models
High VC dimension → flexible models

Higher capacity can fit more patterns but may overfit.

Deep Learning Perspective

Modern AI uses deep neural networks.

Key ideas:

Layers learn hierarchical representations.
Training uses backpropagation.
Large datasets and compute enable strong performance.

Theoretical understanding of why very large neural networks generalize so well remains an active research area in Deep Learning.

